canonical:
  title: 金樞密思亭銘
  author: 李齊賢
  language: lzh
  text: 翼彼亭斯銘之曰思云誰之思父義母慈萬歲之藏陟焉望之維桑之敬伊蒿之悲蠶夜永慕沒齒匪虧籍爾世祿夸爾天資以滿以敖以敖以嬉載瞻斯扁不其恧而子兮子兮尙克念玆
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 金樞密思亭銘
  author: 李齊賢
  language: lzh
  text: 翼彼亭斯。銘之曰思。云誰之思。父義母慈。萬歲之藏。陟焉望之。維桑之敬。伊蒿之悲。蠶夜永慕。沒齒匪虧。籍爾世祿。夸爾天資。以滿以敖。以敖以嬉。載瞻斯扁。不其恧而。子兮子兮。尙克念玆。
korean:
  title: 김추밀 사정 명
  author: 이제현
  language: kor
  text: 날아갈 듯한 저 정자를 명(銘)하기를 사(思)라 한다. 누구를 생각한다는 것일고, 아버지의 옳은 길로 가르치심과 어머니의 자애하심이라. 만세(萬歲)토록 편히 누으신 분묘(墳墓)를 산에 올라 바라본다. 고장의 뽕나무도 공경한다는데 육아(蓼莪) 편의 서러움이라, 새벽이나 밤이나 길이 생각하여 죽는 날까지 잊지 못하리. 너의 세록(世祿)을 믿고 너의 잘난 것만 자랑하여 만족히 여기고 놀기만 한다면 사정(思亭)이란 현판을 볼 때 부끄럽지 아니하랴. 그대여 그대여 매우 생각할지어다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0520_040_0170&viewSync=OT
  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Inscription on Kim's Pavilion of Reflection
  author: Lee Je-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    That pavilion soars like a bird in flight—I inscribe it with the name 'Reflection.'

    Who is it that we reflect upon?
    The righteous guidance of a father,
    The tender compassion of a mother.

    Climbing the hill, I gaze upon the grave
    Where they rest eternal through ten thousand ages.
    The mulberry trees of this place command reverence,
    Yet sorrow weighs upon me like the songs of Ye Ge—
    At dawn and in the depth of night, memory stirs without end,
    A devotion that shall not falter even unto my final breath.

    But if you rely only on inherited fortune,
    If you boast merely of natural gifts,
    If you rest content and know only pleasure—
    Then when you behold this plaque that reads 'Pavilion of Reflection,'
    Will you not burn with shame?

    Young one, oh young one,
    Remember this above all else.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Pavilion of Reflection' (思亭) is named to honor filial piety and the memory of one's parents.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Ye Ge (蓼莪) alludes to a classical poem about filial sorrow and the inability to repay parental kindness.
  - key: ''
    value: This inscription serves as both a memorial and a moral exhortation, warning against the complacency that inherited status and natural talent might breed.
